events.description: The Ostrogoths under Theoderic the Great defeat the forces of Odoacer for the second time.
events.html: • 489 – The Ostrogoths under Theoderic the Great defeat the forces of Odoacer for the second time.

events.description: The Turgesh drive back an Umayyad invasion of Khuttal, follow them south of the Oxus, and capture their baggage train.
events.html: • 737 – The Turgesh drive back an Umayyad invasion of Khuttal, follow them south of the Oxus, and capture their baggage train.

events.description: A magnitude 7.7 earthquake strikes the Caucasus mountains in the Seljuk Empire, causing mass destruction and killing up to 300,000 people.
events.html: • 1139 – A magnitude 7.7 earthquake strikes the Caucasus mountains in the Seljuk Empire, causing mass destruction and killing up to 300,000 people.[1]

events.description: Henry IV is proclaimed king of England.
events.html: • 1399 – Henry IV is proclaimed king of England.[2]

events.description: Suleiman the Magnificent is proclaimed sultan of the Ottoman Empire.
events.html: • 1520 – Suleiman the Magnificent is proclaimed sultan of the Ottoman Empire.

events.description: Spanish conquistador Hernando de Soto and his forces enter Tula territory in present-day western Arkansas, encountering fierce resistance.
events.html: • 1541 – Spanish conquistador Hernando de Soto and his forces enter Tula territory in present-day western Arkansas, encountering fierce resistance.

events.description: A coup by the military establishment of Japan's Ōuchi clan forces their lord to commit suicide, and their city is burned.
events.html: • 1551 – A coup by the military establishment of Japan's Ōuchi clan forces their lord to commit suicide, and their city is burned.

events.description: War of the Austrian Succession: France and Spain defeat Sardinia at the Battle of Madonna dell'Olmo, but soon have to withdraw from Sardinia anyway.
events.html: • 1744 – War of the Austrian Succession: France and Spain defeat Sardinia at the Battle of Madonna dell'Olmo, but soon have to withdraw from Sardinia anyway.

events.description: The first performance of Mozart's opera The Magic Flute takes place two months before his death.
events.html: • 1791 – The first performance of Mozart's opera The Magic Flute takes place two months before his death.

events.description: France's National Constituent Assembly is dissolved, to be replaced the next day by the National Legislative Assembly.
events.html: • 1791 – France's National Constituent Assembly is dissolved, to be replaced the next day by the National Legislative Assembly.

events.description: Georges Bizet's opera Les pêcheurs de perles, premiered in Paris.
events.html: • 1863 – Georges Bizet's opera Les pêcheurs de perles, premiered in Paris.[3]

events.description: Thomas Edison's first commercial hydroelectric power plant (later known as Appleton Edison Light Company) begins operation.
events.html: • 1882 – Thomas Edison's first commercial hydroelectric power plant (later known as Appleton Edison Light Company) begins operation.

events.description: Jack the Ripper kills his third and fourth victims, Elizabeth Stride and Catherine Eddowes.
events.html: • 1888 – Jack the Ripper kills his third and fourth victims, Elizabeth Stride and Catherine Eddowes.

events.description: The Royal Galician Academy, the Galician language's biggest linguistic authority, starts working in La Coruña, Spain.
events.html: • 1906 – The Royal Galician Academy, the Galician language's biggest linguistic authority, starts working in La Coruña, Spain.

events.description: The McKinley National Memorial, the final resting place of assassinated U.S. President William McKinley and his family, is dedicated in Canton, Ohio.
events.html: • 1907 – The McKinley National Memorial, the final resting place of assassinated U.S. President William McKinley and his family, is dedicated in Canton, Ohio.

events.description: The Cunard Line's RMS Mauretania makes a record-breaking westbound crossing of the Atlantic, that will not be bettered for 20 years.
events.html: • 1909 – The Cunard Line's RMS Mauretania makes a record-breaking westbound crossing of the Atlantic, that will not be bettered for 20 years.

events.description: World War I: Radoje Ljutovac becomes the first soldier in history to shoot down an enemy aircraft with ground-to-air fire.
events.html: • 1915 – World War I: Radoje Ljutovac becomes the first soldier in history to shoot down an enemy aircraft with ground-to-air fire.

events.description: Ukrainian War of Independence: Insurgent forces led by Nestor Makhno defeat the Central Powers at the battle of Dibrivka.
events.html: • 1918 – Ukrainian War of Independence: Insurgent forces led by Nestor Makhno defeat the Central Powers at the battle of Dibrivka.[4]

events.description: The Hoover Dam, astride the border between the U.S. states of Arizona and Nevada, is dedicated.
events.html: • 1935 – The Hoover Dam, astride the border between the U.S. states of Arizona and Nevada, is dedicated.

events.description: Britain, France, Germany and Italy sign the Munich Agreement, whereby Germany annexes the Sudetenland region of Czechoslovakia.
events.html: • 1938 – Britain, France, Germany and Italy sign the Munich Agreement, whereby Germany annexes the Sudetenland region of Czechoslovakia.

events.description: The League of Nations unanimously outlaws "intentional bombings of civilian populations".
events.html: • 1938 – The League of Nations unanimously outlaws "intentional bombings of civilian populations".

events.description: World War II: General Władysław Sikorski becomes prime minister of the Polish government-in-exile.
events.html: • 1939 – World War II: General Władysław Sikorski becomes prime minister of the Polish government-in-exile.

events.description: NBC broadcasts the first televised American football game.
events.html: • 1939 – NBC broadcasts the first televised American football game.

events.description: World War II: The Babi Yar massacre comes to an end.
events.html: • 1941 – World War II: The Babi Yar massacre comes to an end.

events.description: The United States Merchant Marine Academy is dedicated by President Roosevelt.
events.html: • 1943 – The United States Merchant Marine Academy is dedicated by President Roosevelt.

events.description: The Germans commence a counter offensive to retake the Nijmegen salient, this having been captured by the allies during Operation Market Garden.
events.html: • 1944 – The Germans commence a counter offensive to retake the Nijmegen salient, this having been captured by the allies during Operation Market Garden.

events.description: The Bourne End rail crash, in Hertfordshire, England, kills 43.
events.html: • 1945 – The Bourne End rail crash, in Hertfordshire, England, kills 43.

events.description: The 1947 World Series begins. It is the first to be televised, to include an African-American player, to exceed $2 million in receipts, to see a pinch-hit home run, and to have six umpires on the field.
events.html: • 1947 – The 1947 World Series begins. It is the first to be televised, to include an African-American player, to exceed $2 million in receipts, to see a pinch-hit home run, and to have six umpires on the field.

events.description: Pakistan joins the United Nations.
events.html: • 1947 – Pakistan joins the United Nations.

events.description: The Berlin Airlift ends.
events.html: • 1949 – The Berlin Airlift ends.

events.description: The U.S. Navy submarine USS Nautilus is commissioned as the world's first nuclear-powered vessel.
events.html: • 1954 – The U.S. Navy submarine USS Nautilus is commissioned as the world's first nuclear-powered vessel.

events.description: Six Indonesian Army generals were assassinated by the September 30 Movement. The PKI was blamed for the latter, resulting in mass killings of suspected leftists.
events.html: • 1965 – Six Indonesian Army generals were assassinated by the September 30 Movement. The PKI was blamed for the latter, resulting in mass killings of suspected leftists.[5]

events.description: Bechuanaland declares its independence, and becomes the Republic of Botswana.
events.html: • 1966 – Bechuanaland declares its independence, and becomes the Republic of Botswana.

events.description: The Boeing 747 is rolled out and shown to the public for the first time.
events.html: • 1968 – The Boeing 747 is rolled out and shown to the public for the first time.

events.description: Jordan makes a deal with the PFLP for the release of the remaining hostages from the Dawson's Field hijackings.
events.html: • 1970 – Jordan makes a deal with the PFLP for the release of the remaining hostages from the Dawson's Field hijackings.

events.description: Malév Flight 240 crashes into the Mediterranean Sea while on approach to Beirut International Airport in Beirut, Lebanon, killing 60.
events.html: • 1975 – Malév Flight 240 crashes into the Mediterranean Sea while on approach to Beirut International Airport in Beirut, Lebanon, killing 60.[6]

events.description: Finnair Flight 405 is hijacked by Aarno Lamminparras in Oulu, Finland.
events.html: • 1978 – Finnair Flight 405 is hijacked by Aarno Lamminparras in Oulu, Finland.[7]

events.description: Ethernet specifications are published by Xerox working with Intel and Digital Equipment Corporation.
events.html: • 1980 – Ethernet specifications are published by Xerox working with Intel and Digital Equipment Corporation.

events.description: The 6.2 Mw  Latur earthquake shakes Maharashtra, India with a maximum Mercalli intensity of VIII (Severe) killing 9,748 and injuring 30,000.
events.html: • 1993 – The 6.2 Mw  Latur earthquake shakes Maharashtra, India with a maximum Mercalli intensity of VIII (Severe) killing 9,748 and injuring 30,000.

events.description: Space Shuttle Endeavour is launched on STS-68.
events.html: • 1994 – Space Shuttle Endeavour is launched on STS-68.[8]

events.description: The Tokaimura nuclear accident causes the deaths of two technicians in Japan's second-worst nuclear accident.
events.html: • 1999 – The Tokaimura nuclear accident causes the deaths of two technicians in Japan's second-worst nuclear accident.

events.description: Israeli–Palestinian conflict: Twelve-year-old Muhammad al-Durrah is shot and killed on the second day of the Second Intifada.
events.html: • 2000 – Israeli–Palestinian conflict: Twelve-year-old Muhammad al-Durrah is shot and killed on the second day of the Second Intifada.[9]

events.description: Controversial drawings of Muhammad are printed in a Danish newspaper.
events.html: • 2005 – Controversial drawings of Muhammad are printed in a Danish newspaper.

events.description: The 7.6 Mw  Sumatra earthquake leaves 1,115 people dead.
events.html: • 2009 – The 7.6 Mw  Sumatra earthquake leaves 1,115 people dead.

events.description: Hurricane Matthew becomes a Category 5 hurricane, making it the strongest hurricane to form in the Caribbean Sea since 2007.
events.html: • 2016 – Hurricane Matthew becomes a Category 5 hurricane, making it the strongest hurricane to form in the Caribbean Sea since 2007.

events.description: Two paintings with a combined value of $100 million are recovered after having been stolen from the Van Gogh Museum in 2002.
events.html: • 2016 – Two paintings with a combined value of $100 million are recovered after having been stolen from the Van Gogh Museum in 2002.
